  "diary": "Started the day right with coffee and checking on my basil and thyme up on the roof—they're really thriving in this early-summer heat. The commute to Georgetown was smooth, though I heard the Light Rail was down most of the day. Lucked out driving.\n\nShiro's was absolutely packed during the USA-Wales match. Everyone wanted wine pairings while glued to the screens, which was actually fun—there's an energy to it. I managed to talk a few folks through a nice Cabernet pairing during the second half. The lunch service flew by. Grabbed a quick bite during my break, then it was straight into dinner prep and the evening rush. A couple of regulars came in, which always makes the shift feel worthwhile. Drove home as the light was fading, feeling pleasantly tired. Spent a little time with my foraging notes before bed—been thinking about hitting the woods near Rattlesnake Lake soon.",
  "thought_process": "The World Cup timing actually worked in our favor today—I knew the early match would draw the lunch crowd, so I made sure my pairings were accessible and solid. The transit closure didn't affect me since I drive, but I was aware some staff might struggle. My mood stayed steady throughout; there's something grounding about being a sommelier on a day like this, helping people enjoy wine while they're caught up in something bigger than themselves. The garden check-in at both ends of the day kept me centered. I chose to focus on the human moments—the regulars, the match energy—rather than just grinding through service. It reminded me why I still love this work at 57.",
